Package com.misc.common.moplaf.job Description

The package provides support for managing Runs. A Run is a piece a logic to be executed as a whole. Support is provided for enforcing its life cycle, for executing it, for monitoring its progress.

The end result of running a Run is a ReturnFeedback. A ReturnFeedback informs the client whether the Run was successful or not, and gives the reason why this was possibly not successful.

A Run supports the following operations

  • Run.run(): start the execution of the Run
  • Run.reset(): initializes an already run Run
  • Run.cancel(): instructs a running Run to Stop

The package provides a mechanism for informing the client whether an operation is possible or not: EnabledFeedback. An EnabledFeedback returns whether the operation is possible or not, and the reason why it is not possible. The EnabledFeedback can be used e.g. for controlling when a user action must be enabled or not. A Run provides the following EnabledFeedbacks.

  • Run.getRunFeedback(): the Run may be started (or run)
  • Run.getResetFeedback(): the Run may be reset
  • Run.getCancelFeedback(): the Run may be cancelled

A Run can be executed synchronously or asynchronously. When executed asynchronously, the Run can inform its execution context (RunContext) about its progress. The execution context can then use it to display the later in e.g. a progress bar. The execution context can inform the Run to stop with the method Run.cancel(). The Run must then at some appropriate moment query if the Run is to be cancelled (Run.isCancelled()) and terminate if required.

A Job is a Run implementing time stamps and a status field.

A JobConsole is a Job managing parameters as received from the commande line

An infrastructure is available for externalizing the parameters of a run. This allows to extract the parameters of a given run or to initialize a run with parameters previously extracted:

  • RunParams: an object supporting parameters
  • ParamsHolder: an object holding set of parameters

A Run can be executed programatically, can be triggered by an action from the user, or can be scheduled. The class com.misc.common.moplaf.job.jobclient.JobScheduler provides an infrastructure for scheduling Runs. This packages provides as well functionality for executing the Run remotely.

Runs can be published in the host environment thanks to the extension point com.misc.common.moplaf.job.emf.run_factory.
